Preheat your oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Chop the @potatoes{3} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel).

Trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed, no need to peel), quarter lengthways then chop into
1cm chunks.

Halve the @chilli{1} lengthways, deseed then thinly slice.

Drain and rinse @lentils{1%pack} in a #sieve{}.

Pop the potatoes onto a lined #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste} then season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to
taste}.

Sprinkle over the @ground turmeric{1%sachet} and toss to coat.

Roast the potatoes on the top shelf of your oven until golden and crispy,
~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Once cooked, remove from the oven and set aside.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Place a large #pan{} over medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @Irish beef mince{250%grams}.

Season with salt and pepper.

Fry until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Break up with a spoon as it cooks.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Mince is cooked
> when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the chopped carrot to the pan and fry until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add @korma curry paste{1%sachet} and chilli (use less if you don't like spice).

Stir together and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Add the @passata{1%pack}, lentils, @chicken stock{1%sachet} powder and
@water{200%ml} to the pan.

Stir together and bring the mixture gently to the boil, then simmer until the
curry has reduced, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Add a splash of water if it needs loosening.

Once the curry is cooked, season to taste with salt and pepper.

Divide the Rogan Josh style beef between #bowls{}.

Lay the roasted potatoes on top.

Serve with a dollop of @yoghurt{150%grams} on the side.

Garnish to taste with any remaining chilli.